body: This Coles store has no microwaveable bacon either.
Picked up the sunshade for the Lumos bike helmet I forgot I ordered. I was just talking about it the day before!
Picked up Katherine from school after her Mathematics exam and then drove straight to Bridgestone once we got home. I was running late and all the school traffic was making progress difficult.

I took the LEAF to Bridgestone to have the rear tyre repaired. But they said the puncture was too close to the sidewall, so had to be replaced. The suggested replacing the two rear tyres, but I asked them to order all four, and this time install Potenza RE003 performance tyres as the grip in the wet is not good. This will reduce the range due to a higher roll resistance, but since most of our driving is on local city roads, this should not be an issue.
I was feeling really tired this afternoon. Anita made a casserole for the first time in 15 years! I had two serves and survived!
Paid $14.95 for a BEAM day pass. Hopefully it will be more economical than paying for the accumulated time at $0.45 per minute.
With the Mens Health appointment done, I decided to walk down to King George Square.
I walked through the Roma Street Parklands. There aren’t any scooters or bicycles up here.
I bought my usual toastie and coffee for lunch and then retrieved my scooter from the carpark
I purchased a day pass because the trip to St Andrew’s Hospital and back was probably going to take longer than the same money on a per-minute basis. Doing the calculations
Dropped the LEAF off at the tyre shop to have the Eco tyres replaced with Potenza RE003 performance tyres. This has all been caused by a nail in the back tyre.
Had more time to kill so had a look around JB HiFi. I bought a Phillips Nose Clippers from their specials bin.
Tyres replaced for $900.00! I hope the range isn’t affected too much?
Drove up Mt Gravatt to test the tyre grip. There seems to be a bit less understeer now.
Bought a loaf of bread and some more Caesar salads

The battery consumption with the new tyres is definitely higher. The round trip to Redeemer consumed 20% charge. That’s a record. It normally used about 14%. That’s an increase of 45%!

Oh well I’ll keep measuring as there can be a large variation. There was more stop-start progress today and the whole trip took 7 minutes longer, so perhaps a few percent can be explained by that.

I packed up the Trangia stove and a Caesar salad and headed off to the Toohey Forest picnic area. As I approached the end of Marshall Rd I realised that I did not have anything to light the fuel for the stove! So I kept going to the Wellers Hill BP Service Station to buy a bic lighter. I’ll keep it in the backpack permanently so this doesn’t happen again.

I set up the Trangia Stove to boil water for the tea. Since there’s a water fountain there I didn’t need to bring any extra water.

I ate the Caesar salad while I waited for the water to boil. There was an especially pesky Currawong taking way too much attention in the stuff on the picnic table. Chasing it away did not work. It just kept coming back each time.

I faced towards the bush today to blank out the other people there. The parking lot seems to be a popular place for tradies to come and sit in their trucks. Maybe they are calling customers etc.
I rode home the long way via the bikeway  down to Bulimba Creek and back.

Just as I got home from the scooter ride, Anita texted that they were going to Garden City to pick up Katherine’s “Just Dance 2022” Nintendo game. I jumped into then LEAF and went there too; but I bought some sushi to bring home. I caught up to Anita on the drive home.
We went for a longer than usual walk! The side show rides were in full swing at the Mt Gravatt Showgrounds.
Parked the LEAF at the QESH AC charger. I had a lot of trouble connecting to the ChargeFox server due to the poor 4G connection there. Fortunately IKEA has free WiFi.

I spent quite a bit of time at Anaconda looking at tents and other camping gear. I bought a Trangia 500ml MultiFuel bottle, a collapsible cup and titanium cutlery.

They sell the non-stick pan for the Trangia, but we’re out-of-stock.
There was a Japanese family there. The noisy kids were playing hide-and-seek around the tents and one was counting down in Japanese.

I turned out the schedule override had reset during all the troubles with the server connection, so the car was not charging. I reenabled the override and went into the IKEA store to have lunch and then see if they had anything new or interesting.
Bought a white plastic wall-mounted paper towel, cling wrap and aluminium foil dispenser as well as a spice rack, since the new dispenser doesn’t have one.
I went straight back to the carpark to wait for Anita and Katherine.
We went home via McDonalds for coffee
I only used 4-5% charge getting to the shopping centre. I decided to use the free charging point to see if it’s worthwhile for a quick shopping trip.

The 20 minutes of charging increased the battery level from 45% to 52% (1.19 kWh or 8 kms @ 6.8km/kWh)

So it was worth it. The trip there and half the trip back again was free.

I installed the paper towel and glad wrap dispenser using some drywall screws of my own. The ones supplied with the holder were hopeless!

One problem I discovered when adding the paper roll was that the width adjustment isn’t enough to hold the roll. Are there different widths available?

I will have to 3D Print some adapters to fix this problem.
Dropped Katherine off at Redeemer for her Food and Nutrition exam.

Bought a proper staple remover. I chose the Rexel product at twice the price of the store brand. They were almost identical in size, shape and design. The Rexel had the additional ability of ejecting the staple; I don’t know if that’s worth the huge difference in price?
Katherine is home on another study day. Her last exam is next week.

I used the Trangia stove to make breakfast this morning. Before starting I filled up the newly purchased Trangia fuel storage bottle. I cooked an egg, bacon, tomatoes and baked beans.

I discovered that the pan is too hot for plastic spatula even if they are supposed to be designed for frying pans. I will have to see if I can get a metal spatula.
I decided to ride to the same place I originally found the fire ants and unfortunately they are still there.
Stopped for a while in the park. Got out the chair and texted Anita and Kiara; I took some photos. I didn’t stay very long as it was getting dark and a storm was threatening.
We are out of eggs and bacon this morning! I will have to go to Cole’s and buy some as soon as I can get ready.

A new Trangia-compatible alcohol stove arrived yesterday, so I tested it this morning by boiling some water. It seems to be faster than original burner; unfortunately the internet was down so I couldn’t set a timer.
It was really humid in the office on Thursday so I turned on the dehumidifier overnight and collected several litres of water!
Dropped Anita off at the Hair Salon.
Went back to pick up Anita from the Hair Salon and then proceeded to MacDonalds to buy breakfast.
Back to MacDonalds again; This time Katherine wanted a Happy Meal.
Walked up to the Pharmacy to get some Calamine Lotion for Anita to treat her rash. She is going to see the GP tomorrow?
While Anita and Katherine were at Myers looking for a Sun Hat, I dropped in to JB HiFi to see if they had the Garmin Tracker (nope). I did end up buying a NanoLeaf Light Strip for the office.
I bought a new shirt! The check out section was busy.
I went straight back to the carpark and waited for Anita and Katherine. They were a while apparently. I must have dozed off for a bit?
We ordered kebabs on the way home.
The first battery lasted up to Tenerife at 8% remaining. I found a shady spot to swap the batteries.
Set up camp at Newfarm Park. I should investigate bringing a system for making tea. I think the Trangia is too bulky for just boiling water, so I might have to buy the gas bottle system?
18% battery consumption. I did seem to catch every traffic light so that would account for 1-2%.
Took Katherine to her Japanese Exam. This is her last high school exam!
Appointment to see physiotherapist prior to surgery
Went the long way home via the Bulimba Creek track and had a break in the park before going home.

Tuesday: Anita and Katherine went to the Redeemer Valedictory Service at the school. I stayed away to reduce my chances of catching anything before the surgery.

To our surprise, Katherine was awarded the co-curricular trophy for her service to the school and community.
Bought a JetBoil Stash. This will be mainly for boiling water to make tea or coffee.
Katherine is making a backpack for University so needed materials to make it.
Coffee stop
A quick walk this evening because the AEVA meeting starts at 7:30pm. We took a detour to see the house that was sold for over a million dollars recently. It’s opposite St Katherine’s school.
Katherine wanted Gravy-loaded Chips and peas for lunch.

Cycles over to the Toohey Picnic area for my own lunch. I tested out the new JetBoil Stash to make tea …twice.

A man stopped to ask about the Nope eBike so my first cup of tea went cold while I was taking to him. The JetBoil was really fast boiling 250mls for the second cup. It must have been less than a minute!

Dropped Katherine off at Shanice’s place. They are all going on a schoolies week at a $5,000.00 per week mansion at Coolum! There are 11 senior students going.

Anita said I have to wait until they leave.
I went the long way round to avoid the local school traffic.

I stopped at Brett’s Wharf to have lunch. There were a couple of BBQ tables and nearby drinking water to make tea using the JetBoil. It was overcast all day except for the time I was there!

I moved to a shady spot under a tree for the rest of the break. Next time I have to figure out how to also bring the table.
I stopped to take a picture of the poinsettia trees in the park.
Anita wanted Whiting and Greek salad for dinner
Using the new eScript system. I think it’s less convenient than the older paper version!
After a quick trip to the newsagent for Anita to buy casket tickets, we had coffee.
Looking to see if they had the collapsible cups for camping - nope. The nylon raincoats are about $90. The ‘pocket-it’ rain jacket.
I bought 7 plastic paper trays with drawers
The WRX needed refueling
We went for a morning walk to get coffee
Had to hurry to the post office to buy a will kit before they closed.
Bought some ear thermometer covers at the chemist.
I went back to the car to wait for Katherine and Anita. They went to Spotlight
Dropped Katherine and Anita off at the old museum for the Queensland Wind Orchestra concert
It took me a while to find this charger only to discover that it wasn’t working.
Drove over to Northshore and charged to 90%. Eat Street was really busy so it was difficult to get there.

The two pharmacists agreed to be witnesses for the last will and testament I made using the post office will kit.

So the will should be good for now. I will do a better one later when there’s more time.

I cleaned up the Chinese bicycle and took it for a short test ride to see what is wrong with the cycle. 

Yes it’s the front wheel bearing on the removable plate side of the motor.

Katherine wanted a cheeseburger for lunch. I ordered a flat white, decaf and banana bread for Anita.

I can’t have anything today because I’m on a clear fluid diet to prepare for the radical prostatectomy scheduled for tomorrow morning.

Dropped Katherine and Anita off outside the BSHS Junior school. It was the most convenient place to stop. They are going to a wind recital that Hanna is playing in, at the cathedral opposite BSHS.

I think I used to walk through the grounds of the church on my walk to and from school to the railway station.
This was my last opportunity to wash the LEAF. I’m not allowed to do any major exercise during the recovery period following the surgery.
Back to West End to pick them up after the concert. This time Katherine wanted KFC so we detoured to the KFC at Eight Mile Plains
Anita drove me to GPH.
Monday: I had a radical prostatectomy today
Monday: Rough time in recovery from pain not fixed with IV opioid. They were worried I wasn’t breathing enough so did an ABG.
